Attorney General John Ashcroft was cleared of violating anti-lobbying laws for promoting the Patriot Act.
The act, passed after 9/11, expanded law enforcement powers against terrorists.
Investigations found no wrongdoing in Ashcroft's speeches supporting the law.
Critics argue the act's surveillance powers are intrusive and rushed.
President Bush and AG Gonzales advocate for renewing the act, emphasizing the balance between security and freedom.
A coalition seeks to repeal controversial provisions, urging Congress to consider civil liberties.
The debate over the Patriot Act intensifies, with calls for transparency and checks on government power.
